SIMPLE: erect
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Erect
<hw>E*rect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>erectus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>erigere</ets> to erect; <ets>e</ets>
out + <ets>regere</ets> to lead straight. See <er>Right</er>, and cf.
<er>Alert</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Upright, or having a vertical
position; not inverted; not leaning or bent; not prone; <as>as, to stand
<ex>erect</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two of far nobler shape, <qex>erect</qex> and tall.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Among the Greek colonies and churches of Asia, Philadelphia is
still <qex>erect</qex> -- a column of ruins.</q>
<rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Directed upward; raised; uplifted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His piercing eyes, <qex>erect</qex>, appear to view⟦br⟧
Superior worlds, and look all nature through.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Bold; confident; free from depression;
undismayed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But who is he, by years⟦br⟧
Bowed, but <qex>erect</qex> in heart?</q> <rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Watchful; alert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vigilant and <qex>erect</qex> attention of mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Standing upright, with reference
to the earth's surface, or to the surface to which it is
attached.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Elevated, as the tips of wings,
heads of serpents, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Erect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Erect
<hw>E*rect"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Erected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Erecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To raise and place
in an upright or perpendicular position; to set upright; to raise;
<as>as, to <ex>erect</ex> a pole, a flagstaff, a monument,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise, as a building; to build; to construct;
<as>as, to <ex>erect</ex> a house or a fort</as>; to set up; to put
together the component parts of, as of a machine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lift up; to elevate; to exalt; to
magnify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That didst his state above his hopes <qex>erect</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, who am a party, am not to <qex>erect</qex> myself into a
judge.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To animate; to encourage; to cheer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It raiseth the dropping spirit, <qex>erecting</qex> it to a loving
complaisance.</q> <rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To set up as an assertion or consequence from
premises, or the like.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>erect</xex>
conclusions.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir T. Browne.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Malebranche
<xex>erects</xex> this proposition.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To set up or establish; to found; to form; to
institute.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>erect</xex> a new commonwealth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Erecting shop</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a place
where large machines, as engines, are put together and
adjusted.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To set up; raise; elevate; construct; build;
institute; establish; found.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Erect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Erect
<hw>E*rect"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To rise upright.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By wet, stalks do <qex>erect</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Erectable</ent>⟦br⟧
